\begin_layout Opening
Dear Editor(s),
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There's been a growing interest in extending the fundamental Bell test to
 continuous variable (CV) systems.
 As originally formulated, the Bell inequality was setup for quantum spins
 which has no classical analogue.
 That it shall possess such peculiarities is therefore, in hindsight, not
 very surprising.
 The known extension to CV systems uses displaced parity measurements; again,
 parity is an inherently quantum phenomenon, and it is pivotal in that scheme.
 Antithetically, here we construct a test using highly classical observables,
 viz.
 modular variables of position and momentum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our approach is particularly distinctive as it neither requires restriction
 of the relevant states to a highly idealized and immured subset, nor is
 it effectively, a vicarious reformulation of the spin half case; we have
 bolstered our result with an experimental proposal, which is based on well
 established multi-slit diffraction techniques, to emphasise this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace vfill
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Closing
Sincerely
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Atul Singh Arora
\end_layout

